article.description: Every Tennessee player scored and played at least 13 minutes in its 86-43 victory over Mississippi.
article.headline: Every Lady Vol plays at least 13 minutes, scores
article.linkText: No. 3 Lady Vols roll to 10th straight victory over Mississippi
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Those who wanted to see No. 3 Tennessee play in a tight contest picked the wrong game to watch Thursday night.

Every Tennessee player scored and played at least 13 minutes in its 86-43 victory over Mississippi.

Gwen Jackson had 19 points and 10 rebounds for Tennessee (19-3, 8-0 Southeastern Conference), which extended its winning streak to 10 games since losing 63-62 in overtime at Connecticut on Jan. 4.

"In games like this it's good for our bench to get minutes like
that,'' Jackson said. "You do it in practice, but playing in a
game is whole lot different.''

The Lady Rebels (12-9, 1-7), led by Amber Watts with 14 points and eight rebounds, have lost 10 straight games to Tennessee.

Poor shooting and rebounding, and too many turnovers by Ole Miss allowed Tennessee to pull away.

   The Lady Rebels got as close as nine points in the first half,
but a 12-0 run early in the second half ensured a blowout.

Jackson started the run with a putback and finished it with a
three-point play for a 25-point lead with 12:35 remaining. She
drove to the basket, and the ball rolled off her hand as she was
suspended in the air above the Ole Miss defenders.

Soon, the reserves were back on the court. Shanna Zolman's
3-pointer with 3:46 left gave the Lady Vols a 77-37 lead.

"They killed us on the offensive boards,'' Ole Miss coach Ron
Aldy said. "Tennessee is a big, strong, physical team, and they
just took it to us.''

Reserves Shyra Ely and Tye'sha Fluker scored 10 points apiece
for Tennessee, which had a season-high 61 rebounds. Ole Miss had
just 32 rebounds.

All 11 Tennessee players had at least three points and one
rebound.

"It definitely helped my confidence being able to play tonight.
I wanted to take advantage of the minutes coach gave me,'' said
LaToya Davis, who was averaging six minutes a game. "These types
of games let us get out there and play hard.''

   Tennessee started the game with a 12-2 run. But coach Pat
Summitt began taking the starters out with about 10 minutes left
before halftime.

All of the starters were on the bench with five minutes to go,
and the Lady Vols' 17-point lead dwindled to nine.

Carletta Brown had a driving basket to start a 9-1 run by
Mississippi, capped by Genice Terry's 3-pointer that trimmed the
lead to 28-19 with four minutes remaining in the first half.

After a timeout 20 seconds later, Summitt left the reserves in,
and they pushed the lead back to 12 at halftime.

"I told the bench they were staying in,'' Summitt said. "I
think they knew at halftime that we had not played the way we are
capable of playing. We didn't have a lot of enthusiasm on the floor.''

Neither team shot more than 33 percent in the first half. Midway through the half, Tennessee was 8-of-27 from the floor while Ole Miss was 4-for-18.
